    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. It's different from classical correlation because classical correlations rely on pre-existing information (like two gloves in separate boxes), whereas entangled particles don't have definite states until measured, and their outcomes are correlated in a way that defies classical intuition.\n\nHere's a quick conceptual breakdown:\n\n1. **Classical Correlation**: Imagine you have two coins, both showing heads. If you flip one and it lands on heads, you already knew the other would be heads because they were prepared that way. The correlation exists because of prior knowledge or shared history.\n\n2. **Quantum Entanglement**: Now imagine two entangled particles. Before measurement, neither particle has a definite state (like \"spin up\" or \"spin down\"). When you measure one, it instantly \"collapses\" into a definite state, and the other particle's state becomes determined at the same time, even if it's light-years away. This isn't just about knowing something beforehand; it's about the particles being fundamentally connected in a way that classical physics can't explain.\n\n**Why it",
      "source": "target",
